        "text": "Michael R. GODLEY & Charles A. COPPEL\n\nThe Pied Piper and the Prodigal Children\n\nA Report on the Indonesian-Chinese Students who went to Mao's China 0)\n\nIn the 1950s and early 1960s, some 60,000 Chinese students left Indonesia for the People's Republic where they quickly disappeared from sight. During the traumatic Cultural Revolution even their closest relatives lost contact. As fate would have it, perhaps eighty percent have turned up as refugees in Hong Kong. Now that their stories are being told (2), it is possible to relate their experiences while reassessing the question of Indonesian- Chinese identity. For the sake of analysis, the students can be divided into three basic groups according to when they went and the circumstances in both Indonesia and the People's Republic. The first migration occurred in the 1950s when China seemed, except for the minority attracted to Taiwan, the only place to continue a Chinese language education. A second wave crashed ashore with the mass repatriation of 1960. The third carried the flotsam from the anti-Chinese storm of 1965-1966.\n\nThe last to arrive, forced out of Indonesia by extreme violence and government closure of Chinese-medium institutions, walked right into the anarchy of the Cultural Revolution. A few found relatives however others just roamed around or became hooligans. The group that went to China in late 1959 or early 1960 were more fortunate. Although they did not always have much choice of institution or course of study, were required to engage part-time in labour and assigned to rural areas after graduation,"
